I'm very late to this video, but perhaps my comments may be of some value to someone. I have sold weedeaters in my time and used them. The instructions warned that it is the TIP of the line that does the cutting, which makes perfect sense because that is the part that's covering the greatest radius, so that it is travelling fastest. It is for this reason that I keep a sharp eye on where the edge of the imaginary "disk" is. In this way I do not tangle the line with anything, so that the motor is never under very much strain. Many of my neighbours have weedeaters and my blood runs cold when I hear the machines bogging down and choking up when shoved into thick growth. Of course, one can't explain anything to them: everyone knows better. My father had a saying that went: "When all else fails, read the instruction." I do that first, before I employ ANY tool or appliance. It's amazing how much one can learn from making a habit of this practice.

Okay this is a tricky one which way do you go with the weed wacker and how do you hold it. So line trimmers are a mechanical scythe made for right-handed use and if you think about using a scythe your natural tendency would be to put your strong arm at the center and your weak arm at the back. But if you're right-handed and you think about pulling that trigger too much you might want to put the trigger in your right hand.... This is wrong! Because the head spins counterclockwise and so you want to move from right to left always with the weed wacker. Have the trigger in your left hand and now you'll be able to walk forward and the grass will get thrown in front of you as opposed to directly backwards at your ankles and face. Doesn't really matter when you're cutting just grass no big deal until you pick up that stick or catch a rock. If you hold it the other way you'll have to walk backwards to get the same effect and you'll take foooorrrrreeeevvvvveeeeerrrrr to do what should take 5-30 min depending how big the yard is. Also if you run your line too long and you're using your trimmer everyday you'll destroy your clutch very quickly. I don't run mine with a guard.   So to get the line equal length and the appropriate length I just turn it sideways and plaster it on the street for a second.

Of course, so many people refer to various products by the name that first made that product popular, hence "weed eater", then on the market " weed wacker ". The correct nomenclature is string line weed trimmer. This was drilled into me by the company rep. when I used to sell Echo products.

Now we can see how billions and trillions of bits of microplastics are being sprayed throughout the environment from these things. The plastic line smashes and shreds and falls in shattered bits into lawns (to become embedded in the soil, accumulating year after year, never dissolving)... and sidewalks, to get washed away by rain, etc., and eventually concentrated into rivers, where fish will digest the powdered plastic bits and eventually die (probably painfully) of either BPA-type toxicity or stomachs filled with collected plastic mash that takes the space away from food that no longer has room to occupy in their stomachs and be digested. Multiply that smashing and shredding times the millions of weed-eaters that have been built so far, and will continue to be built for many more years, and the numbers approach incomprehensibility for the average person.
So fascinating, the complex and almost infinite methods we have developed to eject ever more toxicity into our environment... so slowly and almost invisibly, we won't notice until the damage has become essentially irreparable. In some ways, it appears we are getting "dumber every day"......

BTW, you mentioned right to left.  With a powerful string trimmer (Stihl for example) trimming along a wall from right to left burns more energy (yours) slows progress, and reduces height accuracy.  I've found that traveling the direction the string pulls your trimmer is much easier, better, and faster.  It's easier to slow down the motion than to fight it with opposing force.  I you  have to make more than one pass, it is still quicker and a more uniform cut.  However, if one pass doesn't cut the grass, you might consider ditching the round string in favor of a string with cutting edges.  The larger diameter round string does not always last longer and rarely cuts better.  Force applied to the smallest surface area of the target will always do more damage than equal force applied to a broader surface area.

We call it weed trimmer up here in Vancouver Canada and I am a professional gardener.
I use my trimmer on every working day and what you have experienced in this video is literally what I encounter daily.
To put everything in short and simple format for everyone to understand, trimmer react differently to different material/grass/fence/weed when using different type of string. Thicker string may seems more durable but it still depends on which type of material it is made of and of course the thicker will cost you way more than the non commercial ones.
The length of the string and its force depends on the power your trimmer engine can deliver, but most of them work great when the string is less than 4 inches long; the longer the string is, the less force you will have and less effective to trim the grass/weed.
To effectively use your trimmer, always goes from right to left; and if the grass/weed is quite long (more than 5 inches), trim it down first from the top or your trimmer will 'grab' the grass/weed and stop your trimmer head from rotating.
One thing I want to add is the length of your string could actually damage your trimmer part because the force from countermeasure is too great, your parts will hit a full stop like a metal hitting right into a sturdy wall. That is why to stick with the recommended length is important (that's why there is a metal knife in the guard to cut off the extra length)
My last advice is - take it slow, especially it's a long grass/weed. Remember the string is still made with plastic, its characteristic is not to stay at straight, or you will replace it with metal blade instead. :)

The reason that the weed eater will not run with the line all the way out is because the engine must be tuned to the load that's on the head. So if you wanted to run with trimmer line that's longer than the factory of length you must retune the high-speed and low-speed Jets on the carburetor. That is assuming that the motor itself is able to pull the trimmer head with the amount of weight on the end of it at that RPM. If you had a very powerful weedeater motor you shouldn't have an issue running lines that are extremely long. I see this all the time with people that have lawn mowing businesses that run extremely long and trimmer lines and they can't figure out why they cannot get the engines to run correctly. So if you wanted to retest it take it to a shop and run the line out as far as you wanted to be at and they can tune the engine.

Love the video and the concept!!! One thing to note in particular about the “weed eater” as you southerners call it. You mentioned that the motor won’t rev, in particular with it being a 2 stroke motor, it needs to “supercharge” itself. That means that it the motor was already spinning at high rev and you increase the load, length of string or resistance (grass or objects being trimmed) the motor can handle that better once it is in “supercharged” state. So if you would have had the motor fully revved and then increased the string length you would have stayed at full rev.

When you weedeat from right to left you sling all the grass directly towards you. When you go from left to right it slings it away from you. So if you're cutting along the house line or a garden or somewhere important to be careful around you'll want to walk in the direction that grass gets slung toward you, but any other time you'll want to walk left to right so the grass gets slung away from you and you're not covered in grass and cuts, unless you're in to the sort of thing

Watching the line interact with the fence was really able to highlight the reason that the weed whacker is so ineffective near the fence is that the line needs that full ark to be able to slap the grass apart. Once it hits the fence it basically stops moving and also gets deflected in the opposite direction of it's cutting tension.
That's why you still get some grass cut by the fence, but not all of it; the weed whacker can only cut for the first part of it's ark at the fence material, before it hits the fence.

The breaks on any kind of wire fence is also exacerbated by heat.  Watching your video you can see where the wrapped small loops are partially melting then breaking off as the loop unwinds off the fencing. I always slow down at fence edges to preserve my line.  Grass will still cut and the line won't become shortened by the fence at lower RPM.

It is clear that a lot of care has been given to make the slow motion footage both entertaining, and aesthetically pleasing. The audio that has been added in post certainly gives it a star wars feel. The problem is that all the timy details that go into the sound couldn't possibly be real, and it keeps pulling my attention trying to figure out what made that noise. Things like "notice here how the string is vibrating at [calculated frequency], which is a multiple of the engine rpm" or whatever, you know? There's so much going on that could be explained during those periods of otherwise silence.
Or if the audio is an artistic choice, maybe a text overlay that says that the sound of simulated due to physical constraints in the universe.

Tension break.. you did a Bullwhip video once, right? So when it hits and wraps, that bit gets highly accelerated and puts on the tension.
Why does it pull that direction when you hit the stake? It's not the force of the line hitting the stake, but the balance of forces between the two lines as they rotate. normally, the centrifugal (always get that mixed up) between the lines is more or less balanced. But when you hit the stake, the retreating line has lost a lot of energy, but the advancing line is still pulling on the hub, the forces are unbalanced, and it pulls the head. As the strings switch places, the string that was retreating gets slung outward and becomes the advancing line and snaps taut, while the other line hits the stake and loses its rotational energy.

Just an idea on the failure of the 0.060" fence wire: I agree the weld has an influence but I believe that it is due to the weld causing the fence wire to have very small radius of curvature right on the welded joint. From my commercial experience square line last longer than the round. But I have gone back to using the round. Why? The square has more drag. It's funny you've never considered the line length and engine torque demand. I worked on them while in high school at a small engine repair shop. I always had to tell customers not to remove their guards and also to try and keep the line at its longest length. Reason being if the line is run too short you can actually over speed the engine. If you do it for an extended period of time it can slowly destroy the engine. That was far less common than the other problem though. Most would remove their guards and then come in with a heavily worn engine. Even though it was less than a few months old. It was because they had such an excess load on the thing at all times, it was destroying itself. Not just the engine but the actual shaft and all the bushings and bearings would be so worn from this too. The cutter that regulates the length of the cutting chord not only keeps the engine from over speeding but it keeps the string the same length. Which makes the rotating force much more evenly distributed among the bearings. So if one side of the string is longer than the other, it will destroy the bearings and gears that drive the head.

Thank you for ALL of your awesome videos. I really appreciate the educational content and cannot fathom why anyone would "thumb down" any of them. I do lawn care for a living (30 years of it) and ROUND line is the best. Any of the other shaped lines will have less material in them. For example, The triangle shaped line has a smaller face surface area. You can fit the triangle inside of the circle. The triangle line also wobbles violently up and down. It wont hold straight out for you on the high speed camera, instead it will make an X shape when looking at it eye level. I have wondered if there is some kind of pattern to the wobble with triangle line. Perhaps every 10th rotation makes the line unstable and wobble? That would be cool. Thank you again and your friends and family too, looking forward to your next video.

The best line depends on the operator. Finer line works well for skilled users. The "cheap orange stuff" works for the newbies.

I would love to see how rpms and walking speed effect the interaction. I used to use a balance of line length and speed to get the results I wanted. Along a chain link fence, I would use longer line (I did take the guards off) and lower RPM to get a good amount of drag (picture galaxy arms) when I made contact with the fence. This reduced the likelihood of the line wrapping around the fence, yet still cut the grass. This, in my mind, saved a ton of line.

On say a big thistle, I'd use shorter line, high RPM and come down on it from the top, completely obliterating it.

One thing I noticed right away... In the videos of the "angular" tests it appeared that you never got up to a steady speed and held it. Just basic common sense (in my mind) is that the line will always be "lagging" behind due to drag, but will be more pronounced as the shaft is accelerating, because the line can't "keep up", and is in fact being "pulled" along.
And the different shaped lines have their place. Triangle, Square, and Twisted lines react differently to different materials and strength of materials that you use them on. But one of the most beneficial points of having those lines are that they have an "edge" that helps cut better in different situations. My yard starts to get these really thick weeds that have heavy stalks, where even the best lines still struggle if I don't take it slow and "saw" my way through. I've even tried using those disc attachments, which sometime work better. But for heavy grass the Square or Twisted line is best, and normal round line for light grass. Triangle never performed well. I think because, less sides equals less mass, making a lighter line not having the momentum to cut easily.

It's not often that you find something that Destin/Dustin (sorry I don't know which it is) isn't quite correct about (Or is incomplete in the explanation about), so I'm gonna take this rare opportunity to interject. Around 8:37 Dustin says that the weed-eater hits the rod and the reactionary force causes it to pull away in a straight line. This is true for the first hit, and it does, until the next time that the line hits the rod and the reactionary force of that hit pulls on a slightly different angle to the original one (in the anti-clockwise direction in this video). It's not really seen in the video because the movement is too small but it will continue to hit the rod and pull it in roughly a circle (Really a series of straight lines like a hexagon or octogon with a lot more sides). This is why you feel like it's pulling it in. In reality it's pulling it around. It happens so fast that you feel it all more or less at once. From experience, the effect would be more pronounced the closer the head gets to the rod. It's difficult to explain it further than this without a diagram. Its a similar concept to instantaneous angular momentum and centrifugal force, if that helps.

I use to be a grounds manager charged with maintaining sports fields. Some cool info on grass:

The tearing of the blade isn't healthy for grass. It create a large wound that is easily infected by pathogens and parasites: mostly different types of fungus. Fungus is overwhelmingly the main disease of plants (there are always viruses and parasites but fungus is the most widespread).

A sharp blade is best for cutting grass as a freshly sharpened blade is most likely to induce the smallest wound. A dull blade will create a larger wound by tearing the blade instead of cutting it.

The grass will tend to seal off the area around a wound. This tends to leave a white area, sort of a scar, from the base of the wound to the tip of the wound. If the wound is large enough this will leave a white tip/area on the blade.

If you mow with a dull blade the whole yard will have a lightened hue to it as a result of all the tip of the blades being damaged: you can easily tell if a yard was cut with a dull blade by how white the tips of the grass blades are.

This is also why "mowing" with a string trimmer is typically a bad idea, you always want to mow as much as possible with a sharp blade.

Give it a bump or two and the engine slows back down and off I go. Again, it's just something I kind of do without thinking about it. But after watching this and thinking it all out, that's definitely what I'm doing.

@5:57 “Torque is a function of the length of the line”
No. Torque is constant for any given engine speed. Ignoring the presence of a rev limiter, provided torque is greater than drag, the engine will keep accelerating. When the drag from the line equals the torque of the engine, the engine stops accelerating.

Hey Destin,
Loved the video but I wanted to bring up a few points that you haven't mentioned. You brought up that when wrapping around the wire sometimes it's easier for it to just break off rather than unwrap. I would agree and would like to share my observations from when I've used a weed wacker. I was always fascinated by how the cable of the wacker would heat up during use and especially after hitting a fence or wall. I believe this would be the reason why sometimes it would break at the pinch point of the fence, before it wraps around the fence, or if it broke further down the cable; the point where it's the weakest due to heat (as well as other factors obviously). It would take more testing but I would be interested to see if the places you see with the most damage would be hotter under a thermal camera or, in the case of the high speed in this video, if those points that broke had already hit the fence with no visible damage where I would expect it would instead be hotter then the rest of the cable.
Anyway thanks for continuing the awesome content and the raycon recommendation (I'm gonna get the e55's)

the most interesting thing about the last chicken wire test is that the metal on the vertical sections doesnt break until it is nearly parallel with the horizontal section, and the horizontal section obviously has a tremendous amount more tensile strength than the 4 inch vertical piece, and you can literally see it bend back and forth until it pulls so hard it snaps off at the base. Youre right, that would be the weakest spot, but obviously the metal is so small and flexible that the effect of the connection is actually stronger than the surrounding metal, and it is the opposing tensile forces pulling the metal apart, literally ripping it like a block of cheese torn asunder by dwayne johnson.

The other interesting thing is that at high speeds the nylon (i presume) line becomes almost a liquid, it is pulled so hard, you can see the line hit, stop, wrap around, and then as soon as the head rotation propagates, it snaps it taut almost instantly, pulling it and squeezing it, often either liquefying the plastic or squeezing some liquid chemical component out. Fascinating stuff to watch.

The behavior with the thinnest wire is a great demonstration of how crumple zones work - the wire has some give to it (in some cases a lot of give) and this increases the length of time spent interacting with the weed eater line, similar to a car’s crumple zone spreading out the impact of a car over time. It didn’t seem like any of the weed eater line got cut (or had tension breaks) with the thinnest wire because of this, though that might be due to the limited footage shared for that particular test. In any case, great video - thank you for sharing your curiosity with us Destin!

Awesome video! I had a trimmer with a bump advance, I was trimming by the fence where some volunteer maple trees had sprouted. My line got wrapped around something, and the head pulled into the fence. The RPMs shot up so I knew the line had snapped. I tried to bump it, nothing happened. I stopped it and looked, the spool was empty. Reload the spool, start trimmer, RPMs stay low, and I look, all the line is at my feet? When the line got caught, it pulled so hard it snapped off the pawls that stopped the spool after each bump. I ended up cutting lengths of line, tying a knot in the middle, and threading both ends through the feed hole in the head. When the line wore down I had to stop and change the line for a new knotted section. I bought a new trimmer this year! Stay safe and keep on being excellent to others!

Destin - here something to keep in mind before you do the next part with the pine tests:
Most lines dry out and get brittle over time. You can recover the pliability by soaking the line in water for a few days. Try to buy lines from about the same vintage for your comparison, or alternately soak all of the lines in water for a few days before you test it.
PS: WeedEater is a brand name - the generic description is “string trimmer” or “line trimmer”.
PPS: there’s a lot of design that goes into trimmers - I know, I led design teams for several string trimmers when I worked for B&D.

Hey! First time commenting haha. So, I’ve done my fair share of trimming. Ive worked as a landscaper and also for my local cemetery department before that and had the time to really get intimate with a trimmer. If you want to successfully weed whack around chain link or chicken wire, the key is speed control. You have to go slow and take your time. Let the line wrap the links and shred the grass in between. The same with the corners in nylon fencing. You have to give the line the time to take the shape of the area you’re trying to cut. Would love to see that in slow motion. Also, redmax braided line, .95, is the best line on the planet lol. But a thinner line, like .85 will wrap and take shape into tight areas better even tho it breaks easier. Look forward to the next video.

I have an idea.....
I have been doing lawn care for nearly 18 or so years & love seeing this, 4:19 intrigued me. However, I think "think" there might be a better way to start the process to see if the motor will kick up when its balanced "as the line comes out"........
Setup the camera in front of a piece of plexiglass, high enough to where u can get the trimmer head parallel to the plexiglass.
Start off with the line reeled in, pull the trigger full speed & tap the ground once to get even expand allowing inside to tighten.
Bring the trimmer head up in front of the camera/plexiglass, now tap the glass allowing the line to expand again. Continue till u no longer feel comfortable or assume the experiment is done.
I'm not sure if the motor itself will keep up with the inertia of the line expanding or if there is some kind of governor in the system more-less the motor which keeps in like "underdrive" so the motor doesn't burn itself out trying to push the weight of the lines inertias.

Something i found out on preserving as much string as possible.

If you just use the minimum speed needed to cut light grass against a fence, the string will last a great deal longer.
Not as much torque for the string to snap against the fence, but plenty to cut the grass itself. It's also a good technique to use in unfamiliar area's that may have snaps/poles in them to keep your string from yanking your weed eater around.

It might be that smaller radios objects to wrap around means that the line would break less. When looking at the footage in the video at least the thickest wire had plenty of breaks throughout the test, (although there was probably a few extra breaks due to pinching) but the next thickest wire appeared to have less and I didn't see a single break out of the footage shown.  If you go through the footage and record the ratio of the number of unwinds to hits there might be a relationship you could test. Now this might be due to the effect that the radius of the metal wire used or it might be due to the energy absorbed by the smaller wire as it was able to deform far more under the applied forces. It may be a combination of both though and the only way I could see to differentiate the two effects would be tot use stronger wire. I would also suggest a rig to hold the weed whacker steady in front of a single wire to perform future tests including your different wire shapes tests, this would also save a lot of time in camera setup if the weed whacker was fixed and you swapped out combinations of wires.

Great video as always, but: it would be great if you could explore the environmental impacts of this as well. IMO, weed eaters should be banned because they deposit many millions of pounds of nearly-invisible shredded plastic into the environment every year. I maintain and have maintained properties, and I well understand the need to manage plants, but we really need to let go of the idea that weed eaters are "necessary" or "acceptable" simply because they are convenient and effective. Please consider never using them until and unless truly biodegradable line is one day developed. (There's also the impact of the engines in these things.) Nylon isn't the worst, in terms of pollution, but humans long ago exceeded our morally-acceptable allowance of microplastics dumped on the world, and we shouldn't be using convenience devices that continually shred more of it into the air. There are alternatives: cutting blades and trimmers and such (not to mention strategic landscaping, etc). They don't all work well, but with some research you can put your weed eater behind you and wonder what madness ever made you think it was OK to grind plastic up into the garden. :-) /rant

I'm not sure if this was mentioned in the 6,304 previous comments, but I think the reason the smaller fence broke close to the weld does not have so much to do with the area close to the weld being weakened by the weld itself as it is the bending back and forth stresses of the wire.  That's the same effect you get bending a coat hanger wire back an forth to break it, when you don't have wire cutters on you.  I have done that countless times in my past 59 years.  I have no formal education in stuff like that (big words there!), but I had "Hot Metals and Machining I & II" shop class in high school and have been a machinist for the last 40+ years.  I'm always looking how metal reacts to different cuts and stresses.

Destin, could you do a tension-elongation test to see how much this material stretches before it shows a plastic deformation and until what point it will show an elastic deformation. With this info, the rotations per minute you could calculate the angle at which the plastic string is being pulled and calculate the forces that apply to the string.

Furthermore you could measure the time it takes the strong to rotate around the fence, where it can be seen as immobile. With the rpm of the weed eater you can also calculate the elongation of the string.
Basically with the phantom you've built a visual tension-elongation measurement device.

Shear forces should apply in that case. You've basically got 2 points of failure at least: 1 the impact weakens the plastic string. If the string isn't being broken by the impact, the smallest diameter of the plastic string no carries the weight of the weeed eater pull. After lowering the diameter, tension with a sheer force is being built up until the elastic deformation changes into a plastic deformation which leads to material failure.
Another potential weakening of the string lies in the fact that the string is curled up and therefore shows inner tensions. As we know, inner tensions do get released when heat is applied. This heat is created upon impact with the fence. Basically you use the impact of the string to straighten it out a little and release some of the material tension.

PRO TIP: If your trimmer line breaks too easily, it has become dehydrated and brittle. You can reverse this and make it more flexible, by placing the line in a sealed container, with a wet sponge. Also, I have a very interesting question. I’ve heard here and there that the size of the contact surface does not affect friction. Because the more contact surface you get, the more weight gets dissipated over the surface and you ultimately get the same friction. No problem until here. But, when you think about cars and tyres, wide tyres with larger contact surfaces are considered to produce more friction which leads to higher cornering speed. Not only in the selection of tyres, but also in terms of suspension geometry settings (you must have realized by now that I’m a very car obsessed guy), the settings that let the tyres have the most contact patch brings the most performance. I get so annoyed with this paradox whenever I think about it. I hope you could read this and if you’re ever interested, make it into a video!

Regarding testing different line: it's quite likely that the best type of line to use is the uncoloured line.  The pigments they add to the plastic may just weaken the line so it will not last as long in normal use.  This is the advice I've received from guys who do this for a living.  At the speed this line works I don't expect there to be any significant advantage to shaped line, except maybe to weaken it even further.

13:18 and again at 15:37 my favorite part of the video. the fact that such a tiny bit of wire with such a small mass can have enough momentum from such a short duration of contact, to make the wire continue to bend long, well, "long" after the contact is terminated... combined with the fact that the fence structure is exerting a lot of other forces which are trying to keep that small bit of wire straight... seems kind of incredible to me. it means there's quite a bit more energy at the end of that string than i thought, even when it's being interrupted and slowed down at every turn. and with that in mind, there are some inCREDibly strong weeds in my yard that take a good ten seconds to cut through. well, i actually use blades on my weed-whacker now, so it doesn't take that long. but i'd be interested to know just how much force is being transmitted.
it's crazy to me, seeing such small effects in slow motion. like when you see a car skidding sideways on pavement, to me at least, the tires seem relatively stiff since they have so much pressure in them. but when you see footage of a tire skidding sideways and bouncing around in slow motion, you see all the waves and vibrations and oscillations back and forth... to me it's fascinating to see what i would consider stiff rubber move in such a way that doesn't really seem possible. and the way these minuscule bits of fence wire move in slow-mo is similar. not because they're stiff, but because they have so little mass.

My small electric (ie; weak) strimmer (as we call them here in the UK) doesn't have a blade in the guard to regulate the line length, but rather a short round rod.
It fits with what you've found with the thicker wire fence; the rod is about 3mm in a diameter and around 20mm in length. Its only secured at its lower end, so presumably if the line doesn't break on the first pass, it can slip up and over it to prevent snagging which might cause the line to break at a point closer to the head.
Had always been curious as to why it wasn't a blade and presumed it was for "safety" (to prevent cuts to fingers when changing out the spool) and that it must just rely on "brute force" to snap the line, so this video explains whats happening, perfectly!

Hi! Loving the video but I have an observation here. The smallest wire diameter fence is probably breaking at the welds because that is the most restricted part of the wire. You can see how it just bends the wire when it hits at the middle of wire. At the weld the horizontal lines resist that bending motion, therefore inducing more tension at those spots making it more likely to break. Also it depends who gives in first, the wire or the weld :)

That said the structure of the fence might play a huge roll. Maybe the small diameter diamond shaped fence (like the first) would endure more than this rectangular one...

Seeing all the tiny nylon bits fly off the line as it pulverized itself, got me thinking about the environmental impact of using weed-eaters. I suppose the weeds themselves don't eat up that much line. But accounting for all the weed-eaters in operation across the world, leaves me with the impression that we are creating a lot of micro/macroscopic bits of plastic and just spreading them all around our manicured parts of nature. In the grand scheme of climate change, I don't think weed-eaters should be a priority, but I definitely didn't realize they had as much of a potential impact as they do.

Weedeater is actually a brand of string trimmer and outdoor equipment. It is also the common name in many regions of Canada and the US for a string trimmer. Like many tools there are lots of nicknames such as a "Skill saw" which is really a circular saw. The brand name has become synonymous with the tool. If you call it a string trimmer,  weed whacker, brush trimmer or a number of other names people generally know what you are referring to.....unless you have some unhealthy fascination with marijuana and in that case well there's not a lot that will help with that.

Apologies if this is super obvious, but I have an explanation for why it's better to move the head from left to right.
.
The line is spinning, so on one side it's moving away from you and on the other side it's moving towards you. You want the actual work to be done by the bit that's moving away from you, so that it throws stuff away from you instead of towards you.
.
Also we call them whipper snippers over here, and I wore a whole lot more gear when I was using one growing up:
- Harness
- Gloves
- Earmuffs
- Face shield

8:27 I believe your hypothesis and calculation may not be totally accurate? The force applied to the weed eater's head is a combination of of the pulling force created between where the line wraps around the stake and the point where the line attaches to the head, in conjunction with the leverage created by the rotation of the head pulling the head toward the stake, and the decreasing lateral leverage force as the head rotates 90 degrees from the line being straight forward to where the line is pointing left. There is another force applied to the head which would be angular deceleration of the line as it hits the stake, which would cause the line to want to rotate around it's central balance point in the opposite direction, like when you swing a bat and hit a ball, the ball make the bat's handle want to rotate in the opposite direction around the center of balance. All those forces combined would move the weed eater's head forward and right, but there is another force you may have forgotten about which is that you were not exerting equal resisting force to those forces because the head is on the end of a (approx) 4 foot shaft so it is easy for the head to be deflected left and right, but difficult for it to be deflected forward/backward due to the leverage of that shaft, so if you ran that test again without any shaft I'll bet the weed eater's head would move in a much more y-axis direction rather than an equal x and y axis movement as you showed here.

I've thought about that lag and the motor's ability to deal with excess trimmer line or thicker ground cover. Some heads are designed in such a way that expended clippings or fresh grass can cause the head to get clogged and slow down. Those are lower end heads, usually. It also depends on the trimmer line's dimensions. Is it the inexpensive round .06 or a higher end spiral or hexagonal or square .09 trimmer line?
When we weedeat we do expect a certain amount of resistance and will rev up the engine enough to trim the grass but not damage the tender tree trunk that it's butted up against. Because the disc isn't spinning fast enough to overcomes the resistance that the grass provides but ends will lag behind when it meets the trunk. Or wee need to rev it up to full power so it won't RIP the thick grass I'm trying to cut. I also need to be aware of how much force I'm applying to the rocks that some grass is growing through because I'd rather not throw some errant pebble through my car window. And much of the physics completely escapes me but comes naturally after decades of using a weed eater. I use a Husqvarna 225L.

Not surprising you can hear the torque of the motor,  as that is a function of the moment of inertia of the whole system which is going to consist of the spool of wire + plastic black dohicky of which the later will always have the same moment of inertia because it is unchanged,  the spool of wire will have a moment of inertia that decreases as you go through more wire and there's less mass to spin, the actual strings though while not a super simplistic shape due to them flopping around you can model them though and show that the moment of inertia is proportional to the length² of them,  while it's much to early to do math right now normally the length of line is maybe 10-15cm long, but when you took the guard off and had that string going a meter+ in length you increased the moment of inertia by 50-100 times just due to the length.  Might not think a piece of plastic won't have much of a moment of inertia, but as you could hear from the motor it definitely made a different when you chopped it off completely.

The reason why the weed eater string is curved is quit interesting.
There are 3 forces acting on each bit of the string: the outward "force" (inertia of the string), air resistance and the tensile force of the string.
The outward "force" is straight away from the axis of rotation. The air resistance is against the direction of travel, thus tangent to the circle the string bit is moving.
These 2 forces are perpendicular to each other, so the tensile force (in a balanced system) has to counter act both of them, but also the tensile force points in the direction the string goes.

Imagine the motor starts spinning and the strings are pointing straight. The air resistance is not countered, because the tensile force can only act perpendicular to it, causing the string to bend. The string wil bend until it matches the air resistance. What makes the string curve is that this balance is different on different parts of the string.

(Auto line feed trimmers)
That's how it feeds more line automatically. When the line gets to short, the motor is able to spin faster causing the line mechanism to open and send more line. The line hits the line cutter and the head spins slower causing the line feeder to clamp down again. Sort of like how a centrifugal clutch works but in reverse.
If there is a wiggle or a wave in the line as it spins, the motor will not rev all the way up however, if you can get the resonance right, it will. It's tricky but, it can b done. Experiment with it.
